SKUKUZA &#8211; Forensic testing is taking up a position at the forefront of the war against poaching. Yet, the scientists applying cutting-edge technology to help fight illegal trade in rhino horn are not found in state-of-the-art offices and laboratories, as seen on television.In the Kruger National Park (KNP) a customised bakkie is the training laboratory at the offices of Missions Area Joint Operations Centre (Majoc). Science is at the heart of the process used to backtrack to a crime scene where rhino horns were confiscated. Twenty five SAPS men and women, from as far as Springbok in Namaqualand, are being trained by the police unit responsible for rhino-related crimes, stock theft and endangered species.